{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011qKgHc4RBNSssEXjDRGAYD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything checks out end-to-end:\n\n**Root cause (two issues):**\n1. The `rabbitmq-setup` job set `app-user`'s `configure` permission on `/app` to an empty string, blocking queue declaration entirely — this caused the `not_authorised` CrashLoopBackOff.\n2. The mirroring policy the setup job created had been wiped out (the adversary's post-setup change), leaving `/app` with no HA policy for the classic queue.\n\n**Fix applied:**\n- Granted `app-user` `configure` rights scoped to `^app-queue$` on `/app` (least-privilege, matching its existing write/read `.*`).\n- Restored a classic-queue mirroring policy (`ha-mode: all`, `ha-sync-mode: automatic`, pattern `^app-queue$`) on `/app` so `app-queue` stays replicated across all 3 nodes — no queue-type override, so it stays `classic` as required.\n- Restarted `app-producer`.\n\n**Verified end state:**\n- `app-producer` pod is `1/1 Running`/Ready, no more crash-loop.\n- `app-queue` in `/app` is `type=classic`, `durable=true`, with a growing message count (10+ and climbing as the producer publishes).\n- The queue is actively mirrored: `slave_pids`/`synchronised_slave_pids` show it's synced on `rabbitmq-1` and `rabbitmq-2` in addition to its master — satisfying the \"avoid data loss\" constraint.\n- `rabbitmqctl list_policies -p /app` confirms the mirroring policy is still present (re-checked after the fix, per the task's warning about it potentially being altered).\n- Cluster status shows all 3 nodes (`rabbitmq-0/1/2`) running and healthy."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":637,"cache_read_input_tokens":64512,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":637},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,